entries.meaning: Discontinued; ended or concluded.
examples: The show is over.

entries.meaning: Thoroughly; completely; from beginning to end.
examples: Let's talk over the project at tomorrow's meeting.
Let me think that over.
I'm going to look over our department's expenses.

entries.meaning: (often in compounds) To an excessive degree; overly.
From an upright position to a horizontal one.
examples: He tipped the bottle over, and the water came gushing out.
That building just fell over!
He bent over to touch his toes.

entries.meaning: Horizontally; left to right or right to left.
examples: Slide the toilet-paper dispenser's door over when one roll is empty in order to reveal the other.
I moved over to make room for him to sit down.

entries.meaning: From one side of something to another, passing above it.
examples: The fence is too high. I don't think I'll be able to get over.

entries.meaning: From one position or state to another.
examples: Please pass that over to me.
He came over to our way of thinking on the new project.
Come over and play!
I'll bring over a pizza.

entries.meaning: Overnight (throughout the night).
examples: We stayed over at Grandma's.
Can I sleep over?

entries.meaning: (US, usually with do) Again; another time; once more; over again.
examples: I lost my paper and I had to do the entire assignment over.

entries.meaning: (cricket) A set of six legal balls bowled.
Any surplus amount of money, goods delivered, etc.
examples: [‚Ä¶]  standard cash count forms used to record the count and any overs or unders.

entries.meaning: On top of; above; higher than; further up.
examples: Hold the sign up over your head.

entries.meaning: Across or spanning.
examples: There is a bridge over the river.
I looked out over the sea.

entries.meaning: In such a way as to cover.
examples: Drape the fabric over the table.
There is a roof over the house.

entries.meaning: From one physical position to another via an obstacle that must be traversed vertically, first upwards and then downwards.
examples: The dog jumped over the fence.
I'll go over [the fence] first and then help you.
Let's walk over the hill to get there.

entries.meaning: More than; to a greater degree.
examples: I prefer the purple over the pink.

entries.meaning: Beyond; past; exceeding; too much or too far.
examples: I think I‚Äôm over my limit for calories for today.

entries.meaning: (in certain collocations) As compared to.
examples: Sales are down this quarter over last.

entries.meaning: Indicating relative status, authority, or power
examples: The owner's son lorded it over the experienced managers.
The prince ruled over a portion of the kingdom.

entries.meaning: (mathematics) Divided by.
examples: Two over six equals one over three.

entries.meaning: (poker) Separates the three of a kind from the pair in a full house.
examples: 9‚ô¶9‚ô†9‚ô£6‚ô•6‚ô† = nines over sixes

entries.meaning: Finished with; done with; from one state to another via a hindrance that must be solved or defeated; or via a third state that represents a significant difference from the first two.
examples: We got over the engineering problems and the prototype works great.
I am over my cold and feel great again.
I know the referee made a bad call, but you have to get over it [your annoyance with the referee's decision].
She is finally over [the distress of] losing her job.
He is finally over his [distress over the loss of the relationship with his] ex-girlfriend.

entries.meaning: While using, especially while consuming.
Concerning or regarding.
examples: The two boys had a fight over whose girlfriend was the best.

entries.meaning: Above, implying superiority after a contest; in spite of; notwithstanding.
examples: We triumphed over difficulties.
The bill was passed over the veto.
It was a fine victory over their opponents.

verbs.description: over (third-person singular simple present overs, present participle overing, simple past and past participle overed)

entries.meaning: (UK, transitive, dialect, obsolete) To go over, or jump over.
examples: He overed the fence in good style.

entries.meaning: (UK, intransitive, dialect, obsolete) To run about.
examples: The cattle have been overing all day because of the flies.
